summary_lines.append('')
summary_lines.append(f'Iteration 8 showed that growth rate was the main broad dependency covariate. Top-quartile growth shifted dependency_POLR2A by {R[\"POLR2A_growth_hi\"][\"effect\"]:.4f} (p={fmt_p(R[\"POLR2A_growth_hi\"][\"p\"])}), the largest general growth-associated effect. It also shifted dependency_TMED10 by {R[\"TMED10_growth_hi\"][\"effect\"]:.4f} (p={fmt_p(R[\"TMED10_growth_hi\"][\"p\"])}). Within high-growth lines, basal subtype was less TMED10-dependent by {R[\"TMED10_basal_within_growth\"][\"effect\"]:.4f} (p={fmt_p(R[\"TMED10_basal_within_growth\"][\"p\"])}), suggesting a suppressive subtype context for that otherwise weak outcome.')
summary_lines.append('')
summary_lines.append('Iteration 9 performed the required systematic dependency-heterogeneity search for every dependency outcome using single predicates and pairwise conjunctions over lineage, subtype, culture, batch, binary genomic features, and top/bottom quartiles of continuous features, with a minimum subgroup size of 300. The interpretable best-supported subgroups were: BRAF with braf_v600e=1; EGFR with egfr_amplification=1; ERBB2 with erbb2_amplification=1; KRAS with kras_mutation=1; RIT1 with nf1_loss=1 plus brain lineage; KIF18A with colorectal/APC-mutant/WNT-high/SMAD4-retained status; TMED10 with high growth, with a smaller high-growth prostate subgroup; DHX9 with high MYC RNA plus high growth; POLR2A with high growth; and RPL11 with MYC amplification plus high growth.')
summary_lines.append('')
summary_lines.append(f'Iteration 10 checked robustness of the four canonical oncogene effects in adjusted OLS models including lineage, culture_type, screen_batch, cas9_activity_score, and growth_rate_doublings_per_day. The adjusted coefficients remained large and negative: BRAF {R[\"BRAF_adj\"][\"effect\"]:.4f}, EGFR {R[\"EGFR_adj\"][\"effect\"]:.4f}, ERBB2 {R[\"ERBB2_adj\"][\"effect\"]:.4f}, and KRAS {R[\"KRAS_adj\"][\"effect\"]:.4f}; all retained p-values below numerical precision or far below 0.05. This supports the interpretation that the primary oncogene dependencies are not artifacts of screen batch, culture, growth, or lineage composition.')
summary_lines.append('')
summary_lines.append('Overall conclusions: the strongest biological effects were alteration-matched oncogene dependencies for BRAF, EGFR, ERBB2, and KRAS; an NF1-loss/RIT1 dependency with brain-lineage intensification and EGFR-amplification suppression; a highly specific KIF18A dependency requiring colorectal lineage, APC mutation, high WNT activity, and retained SMAD4; MYC/growth-associated RPL11 and DHX9 dependencies; and a broad high-growth dependency signal for POLR2A and, more weakly, TMED10. Refuted or weakened hypotheses included skin-specific amplification of the BRAF V600E effect and pancreatic-specific amplification of the KRAS mutation effect.')

